    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Increasing hydration levels can indeed impact the dynamics of your sourdough starter. A wetter starter can lead to a more rapid transfer of nutrients from the flour to the microorganisms, as the increased water availability facilitates the solubilization of starches. This can result in a more rapid breakdown of starches, which can, in turn, affect the enzyme activity. The wild yeast and lactobacilli can move more freely in a wetter environment, allowing them to colonize the substrate more efficiently. However, this increased water availability can also lead to a more rapid depletion of nutrients, potentially favoring the growth of lactobacilli over the wild yeast. This is because lactobacilli are more tolerant of acidic conditions and can thrive in a more water-rich environment.",
